            <h2><i>4.2.5 Bladder dysfunction</i></h2>
            <h3><i>Background</i></h3>
            <p>
                Bladder dysfunctions occur in over three-quarters of PwMS but only one third will actively seek help<sup>124</sup>. Different bladder dysfunctions are 
                associated with different courses of the MS trajectory.
            </p>
            <p>Bladder symptoms typical early in the MS trajectory include: </p>
            <ul>
                <li><span>Urgency</span></li>
                <li><span>Nocturia</span></li>
                <li><span>Frequency </span></li>
                <li><span>Incontinence </span></li>
            </ul>
            <p>Bladder symptoms typical later in the MS trajectory (when lower limb spasticity develops) include: </p>
            <ul>
                <li><span>Hesitancy</span></li>
                <li><span>Incomplete emptying </span></li>
                <li><span>Retention<sup>125</sup> </span></li>

            </ul>
            <p>A hyperactive bladder is the most common bladder dysfunction experienced by PwMS. </p>
            <p><b>See module 4 section 4.6 for more information on management of bladder dysfunctions.</b></p>
            <h3><i>Rehabilitation</i></h3>
            <p>Many PwMS develop hyperactivity of the detrusor muscle which causes bladder irritation and frequent voiding of small amounts of urine. If feasible, 
                post-void residual (PVR) urine levels can be monitored. The goal is to have <100 ml PVR, and a continent patient. Reducing fluid intake to <2000 ml/day 
                can help in achieving this. </p>
            <p>Hyperactive bladder rehabilitation can consist of the below rehabilitative interventions.</p>
             <ul>
                <li><span><b>Pelvic floor muscle training</b> (PFMT) – these are exercises (applicable for both sexes) that strengthen the pelvic floor.</span></li>
                <li><span><b>Intravaginal neuromuscular electrical stimulation</b> (NMES) – sends electric pulses or signals to precise areas of the weakened muscles in the pelvic area, causing them to contract and relax. These transmitted via electrode pads placed on the surface of the skin or by using an electrode probe vaginally or anally. </span></li>
                <li><span><b>Transcutaneous tibial nerve stimulation</b> (TTNS) – is designed to indirectly stimulate the nerves that are responsible for bladder control. Small electrodes are placed on the skin by the ankle. Electrical signals travel along nerves and aid in retraining bladder function. </span></li>
                
            </ul>
            <p>Evidence from a 2016 study on women with MS suggested PFMT alone or in combination with intravaginal NMES or TTNS is effective in the treatment of 
                overactive bladder. Decreases in urgency, incontinence, hesitancy, incomplete bladder emptying and nocturia were all recorded<sup>126</sup>. </p>

            <h2><i>4.2.6 Bowel dysfunction</i></h2>
            <h3><i>Background </i></h3>
            <p>Bowel dysfunction occurs in over three-quarters of PwMS and is usually associated with bladder dysfunction<sup>127,128</sup>. As with bladder dysfunctions, 
                bowel dysfunctions in PwMS can contribute to social retirement, depression, reductions of sexual activity, increased spasticity, skin infections 
                and abdominal pain. Common symptoms include:</p>
             <ul>
                <li><span>Delayed gastric emptying</span></li>
                <li><span>Constipation</span></li>
                <li><span>Faecal incontinence </span></li>

            </ul>
            <h3>Rehabilitation </h3>
            <p>The MS nurse is often the lead member of the MDR team when developing bowel management interventions<sup>129</sup>: </p>
            <ul>
                <li><span>Establishing a regular bowel voiding pattern is an early step; attempting to defecate 20-30 minutes after ingesting a meal is recommended<sup>130</sup> </span></li>
                <li><span>Managing fluid intake (2 L/day) and encouraging regular exercise</span></li>
                <li><span>Ensure adequate daily dietary fibre intake (15 g/day) results in softer and bulkier stools – improves transit time, constipation and incontinence<sup>131</sup> </span></li>
                <li><span>Abdominal massage increases the frequency of defecation </span></li>
                <li><span>Bulk forming, softening and stimulating drug agents can be utilised to aid bowel dysfunction</span></li>
                <li><span>Rectal suppositories and laxatives may also be used </span></li>
            </ul>
            <p>For neurogenic bowel dysfunctions, an individualised but multidisciplinary rehabilitative approach using a combination of physiotherapeutic 
                and possibly drug interventions is advisable. </p>
            <p><b>See module 4 for more information on management of bowel dysfunctions.</b></p>

            <h2><i>4.2.7 Swallowing dysfunctions</i></h2>
            <h3><i>Background</i></h3>
            <p>
                <a href="#" class="deepdive" rel="deepdivepopup4">Swallowing problems (dysphagia)</a> frequently occur throughout the trajectory of MS, affecting 
                over one-third of PwMS<sup>132</sup>. Dysphagia is more 
                typically a feature of advanced, progressive MS but it can occur in PwMS with non-progressive courses. As MS Nurses are often the first point of 
                contact in rehabilitation centres for a PwMS, they should be adept at recognising the symptoms of dysphagia. The primary swallowing symptoms of 
                dysphagia can occur singly or in combination in PwMS<sup>133</sup> and include:  
            </p>
             <div id="deepdivepopup4" class="deepdivepopup">
                <p>
                  <b>Dysphagia</b> is a disturbance of the complex sensorimotor functions of swallowing. Neurogenic dysphagia (ND) is dysphagia resulting from a neurological 
                    disease. In ND, disturbances of the oral and/or pharyngeal phase are very frequent, in contrast to rarely-occurring oesophageal 
                    problems (‘oropharyngeal dysphagia’).
                </p>
            </div>
            <ul>
                <li><span>Very frequent swallowing </span></li>
                <li><span>Increased saliva</span></li>
                <li><span>Regurgitation of food through the nose  </span></li>
                <li><span>Wet and gurgling voice  </span></li>
                <li><span>Repeated swallowing to empty the larynx </span></li>
                <li><span>Altered head posture during swallowing </span></li>
                <li><span>Coughing during food or fluid ingestion  </span></li>
                <li><span>Reducing food or fluid  </span></li>
                <li><span>Eating/drinking smaller amounts of food/fluids</span></li>
                <li><span>Repeated fever or pneumonia </span></li>
            </ul>
            <h2><i>Rehabilitation</i></h2>
            <p>
                Goals for dysphagia rehabilitation should be aimed at preserving or returning PwMS to a normal diet, improving their nutritional status and 
                reducing opportunity for developing aspiration pneumonia<sup>134,135,136</sup>. Some common rehabilitative interventions are described below.
            </p>
            <h3><i>Restorative interventions</i></h3><br />
            <ul>
                <li><span>Stimulation of face, mouth and tongue (e.g., stretching, pressure, brushing, thermal stimuli)</span></li>
                <li><span>Functional exercises of tongue and lips, speech breathing and vocal exercises, Masako manoeuvre (i.e. tongue holding)</span></li>
                <li><span>Thermal stimulation for triggering the swallow reflex</span></li>
            </ul>
            <h3><i>Compensatory interventions</i></h3><br />
            <ul>
                <li><span>Manoeuvring posture to modify pharynx shape and redirect bolus material – preventing aspiration</span></li>
                <li><span>Training of specialised swallowing techniques (e.g., ‘double swallow’)</span></li>
                <li><span>Delivering food via better half of tongue (if applicable)</span></li>
                <li><span>Adapting diet to include more mashed foods and thickened beverages</span></li>
                <li><span>Use of compensatory eating and drinking devices</span></li>
                <li><span>Ensuring upright positioning of body and head </span></li>

            </ul>
            <p>
                Dysphagia affects QoL, especially in terms of activity limitation and participation restriction. Outcome measures used to evaluate dysphagia 
                rehabilitation should therefore be based upon clinically relevant rather than surrogate end-points e.g., SWAL-QOL<sup>137</sup> .
            </p>
            <p><b>More information on swallowing dysfunctions can be found in module 2 </b></p>
